  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real, tangible worry that's been weighing on my family and me for years. Growing up in a small Italian town, I never had the chance to explore advanced math or science in school, and my parents only went to primary school themselves. That's why I always felt like I wasn't 'smart enough' for these subjects, even when I tried hard. Stereotype threat is when people feel anxious about confirming negative stereotypes about their group, and in STEM fields, this often means girls, women, and people from underrepresented backgrounds feel like they don't belong. For me, it was about not being confident in my abilities, which made me avoid STEM subjects altogether. Now, as a retired man living in Naples, I've seen how this anxiety can hold back young people from reaching their full potential. Should we address it? Absolutely. We need to change the way we talk about STEM in schools and communities, especially in places where people feel they don't fit in. For example, in my neighborhood, there are few role models in STEM, which makes it harder for kids to see themselves in those fields. I've learned through yoga and running that small, consistent efforts—like encouraging kids to try new things without fear—can make a big difference. But we also need to tackle the bigger picture: making sure everyone feels welcome and supported, not just in classrooms but in the wider community. I'm anxious about this issue because it affects so many people, and I worry that without action, future generations will miss out on the opportunities they deserve.",
